Distribution of the interest rate

p1 = df_loan %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = (interest_rate))) +
  geom_histogram(aes(y=..density..),binwidth=1) + 
  geom_density(colour="Red")
p2 = df_loan %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = log(interest_rate))) +
  geom_histogram(aes(y=..density..),binwidth=0.1) + 
  geom_density(colour="Red")
plot_grid(p1, p2)

The summary of the homeownership

df_loan %>% group_by(homeownership, emp_length) %>%
  summarize(cnt = n()) %>%
  ggplot(., aes(x=factor(emp_length), y=cnt, fill=homeownership))+
  geom_bar(stat='identity', position=position_dodge(0.7))+ 
  xlab("Employee Length (Years)") +
  theme(axis.text.x=element_text(angle=90 ,hjust=1, vjust=0.5))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'homeownership'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.

Employee Length and Interest Rate

df_loan %>%
  ggplot()+
  geom_boxplot(aes(x=factor(emp_length), y=(interest_rate)))+ 
  xlab("Employee Length (Years)") +
  ylab("Interest Rate (%)") +
  theme(axis.text.x=element_text(angle=90 ,hjust=1, vjust=0.5))

The distribution suggested that the length has no strong relationship with the rate.

States

p1 = df_loan %>% group_by(state, grade) %>%
  summarise(cnt = n()) %>%
  ggplot(., aes(x=reorder(state, -cnt), y=cnt, fill=grade))+
  geom_bar(stat='identity', position='stack')+ 
  xlab("States") +
  theme(axis.text.x=element_text(angle=90 ,hjust=1, vjust=0.5))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'state'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.
p2 = df_loan %>% 
  ggplot() +
  geom_boxplot(aes(x=factor(state), y=(interest_rate)))+ 
  xlab("States") +
  ylab("Interest Rate (%)") +
  theme(axis.text.x=element_text(angle=90 ,hjust=1, vjust=0.5))

plot_grid(p1, p2)

Annual Income to Interest Rate

df_loan %>% 
  ggplot(., aes(x=annual_income, y=interest_rate, colour=grade))+
  geom_point(size = 1)+
  xlab("Annual Income") +
  ylab("Interest Rate")

# Grade, Subgrade and Interest Rate
df_loan %>%
  ggplot()+
  geom_boxplot(aes(x=factor(grade), y=(interest_rate), color=))+ 
  xlab("Employee Length (Years)") +
  ylab("Interest Rate (%)") +
  theme(axis.text.x=element_text(angle=90 ,hjust=1, vjust=0.5))

The result suggested that the interest rate should formed based on the attribute.

Also, grade might be the intermediate attributes from other factors to the rate. For further analysis, we should consider to exclude this attribute for building models.

df_customer = read_csv("casestudy_q2.csv")
## New names:
## * `` -> ...1
## Rows: 685927 Columns: 4
##  Column specification 
## Delimiter: ","
## chr (1): customer_email
## dbl (3): ...1, net_revenue, year
## 
##  Use `spec()` to retrieve the full column specification for this data.
##  Specify the column types or set `show_col_types = FALSE` to quiet this message.
df_stack <- melt(df_customer_result[,c('Year', 'New Customer Revenue', 'Existing Customer Growth', 'Existing Customer Revenue (Previous)')], id.vars = 1)

ggplot(df_stack, aes(x = factor(Year), y = value)) + 
    geom_bar(aes(fill = variable), stat = "identity", position = "stack")

The growth of existing customer is trivial, most of the revenue is from acquiring new customers.

df_customer_result$`Lost Customers` = -df_customer_result$`Lost Customers`
df_customer_result$`Existing Customers` = df_customer_result$`Total Customers (Current)` - df_customer_result$`New Customers`
df_stack <- melt(df_customer_result[,c('Year', 'New Customers', 'Existing Customers', 'Lost Customers')], id.vars = 1)

ggplot(df_stack, aes(x = factor(Year), y = value)) + 
    geom_bar(aes(fill = variable), stat = "identity", position = "stack")

For each each the returned customers are less than the customers they lost. Most of the customers are formed by new acquired customers.
